{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 00:03:31.162038", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary\\n- Overall IP connectivity across the enterprise network is healthy. Routing between user subnets and the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) works with low latency and no loss in sampled tests.\\n- Critical anomaly: DNS service on dns_server (10.200.0.2) is down. Hosts cannot resolve local zone names (e.g., web99.local, web0.local…web3.local). HTTP services are reachable by IP, indicating the issue is isolated to DNS rather than routing or server applications.\\n\\nNetwork Health Assessment\\n- L3 reachability: Broad ping matrix shows 0% loss and millisecond RTTs between representative access hosts and server-farm addresses. Sampled pings dhcp_server/dns_server to access hosts also succeed.\\n- Server farm reachability by IP:\\n  - Load balancer at 10.200.0.7 responds to HTTP with typical start-transfer ≈0.2–0.35s and total ≈1.0–1.15s from hosts in different access domains.\\n  - Web servers 10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6 respond similarly to HTTP requests by IP.\\n- DHCP hint: Hosts have valid IPs in expected subnets (10.<core>.<dist>.*), implying DHCP and relay are functioning.\\n\\nDetected Anomalies\\n1) DNS outage for the local zone\\n   - Symptom (hosts): DNS queries from multiple access hosts fail with “connection refused” to 10.200.0.2:53.\\n     - Evidence:\\n       - resolv.conf on hosts points to nameserver 10.200.0.2 (expected).\\n       - dig @10.200.0.2 web99.local web0.local … returns “connection refused” and “no servers could be reached”.\\n       - Pings to 10.200.0.2 from hosts succeed (0% loss), so L3 path is fine.\\n   - Symptom (apps): curl to http://web99.local and http://webN.local fails to name-resolve (namelookup 0.000000; effectively no request issued), while curl to IPs (10.200.0.7, 10.200.0.3–.6) works, confirming the break is at DNS.\\n   - Localization and root cause:\\n     - On dns_server:\\n       - No process listening on port 53 (netstat shows no TCP/UDP 53 sockets).\\n       - systemctl shows named.service loaded/enabled but Active: inactive (dead). bind9.service is loaded/disabled, also inactive (dead).\\n     - Conclusion: DNS daemon is not running on dns_server; port 53 is closed. This is the proximate root cause of the name-resolution failure.\\n\\n2) Minor observations\\n   - Latency variance: Occasional higher RTT outliers (e.g., ~16 ms in a single sample) were observed in the synthetic matrix but with no packet loss and normal medians. These appear transient and not service-impacting given current evidence.\\n   - OSPF/Routing: Not directly inspected via FRR commands in this run, but end-to-end connectivity across many subnets and to 10.200.0.0/24 by IP strongly indicates IGP is converged and routes are present.\\n\\nImpact Assessment\\n- Users cannot access services by FQDN (e.g., web99.local, web0.local…web3.local). This affects any workflows relying on DNS resolution.\\n- Direct IP access to services is functional and demonstrates the application and load-balancing tiers are reachable and operating over the network.\\n\\nMost Probable Root Cause\\n- The DNS server process (named/BIND) on dns_server (10.200.0.2) is down/inactive, leaving UDP/TCP port 53 closed. This leads to immediate “connection refused” to all DNS queries from hosts and breaks name-based access to services.\\n\\nFaulty Device(s)\\n- dns_server (10.200.0.2): DNS application layer (named/BIND) not running.\\n\\nNo remediation steps are proposed here per the request., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='2a3a8e54-3596-4430-91b7-aea6b861b083'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
